{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472633"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:00:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:00:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1551"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1551"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.11,0.14,0.17,0.39]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1551"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92200"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1551"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1551"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75529"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"823"},{"type":"tags","id":"1186"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27569"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31452"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31453"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31463"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92200"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with persistent right forearm pain for three weeks following a fall at school. Initially, he continued his usual activities despite the pain. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is tenderness over the distal ulna but full range of movement of the right elbow, forearm and wrist. There is no deformity, swelling, or bruising.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn X-ray reveals a distal ulnar fracture (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following features is present on the X-ray?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No obvious associated abnormality","Soft tissue swelling","Angulation","Radioulnar dislocation","Callus formation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case demonstrates a healing distal ulnar fracture in a child. The presence of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecallus formation\u003C/strong\u003E on X-ray is characteristic of the bone healing process, typically visible 2-3 weeks after injury, which matches the timeline in this case. Callus formation represents new bone growth around the fracture site and is a normal part of the healing process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is \u003Cstrong\u003Eno obvious associated abnormality\u003C/strong\u003E beyond the fracture and callus formation. The initial injury was likely a buckle (torus) fracture, which is common in children due to the elastic nature of their bones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESoft tissue swelling\u003C/strong\u003E would be expected in the acute phase of injury but would typically resolve by three weeks. The examination findings confirm there is no current swelling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAngulation\u003C/strong\u003E is not present in this case. While angular deformity can occur with paediatric fractures, the description indicates good alignment of the fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadioulnar dislocation\u003C/strong\u003E is a more severe injury that would typically cause significant functional impairment and would be unlikely to present with preserved range of movement as described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights how children can sometimes present late with fractures due to their ability to compensate well and maintain function. The presence of callus formation helps date the injury and confirms the history provided. Treatment at this stage typically involves immobilisation to allow complete healing, with good outcomes expected given the natural remodelling capacity of children\u0027s bones.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Callus formation on X-ray indicates bone healing and typically appears 2-3 weeks after a fracture","Children\u0027s fractures may initially be subtle and present late due to good compensation and continued function","Buckle (torus) fractures are common paediatric injuries due to the elastic nature of children\u0027s bones"],"references":["Patel DS, Statuta SM, Ahmed N. Common Fractures of the Radius and Ulna. Am Fam Physician. 2021; 103:345354"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75529"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1551"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"479"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/479"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4e244702-b6bb-47ca-8d8a-8c03e2fc43ac.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4e244702-b6bb-47ca-8d8a-8c03e2fc43ac.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":436,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75529"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-16T20:39:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-16T20:39:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1551"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92200"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"de